Looking at the code fragments and the Hexi library patterns, I can implement the functions for reading and writing to the dynamic_buffer. Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/dynamic_buffer.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
void write_to_dynamic_buffer(hexi::dynamic_buffer<block_size>& buffer, uint32_t header, const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    // Write header first (4 bytes for uint32_t)
    buffer.write(reinterpret_cast<const uint8_t*>(&header), sizeof(header));

    // Write data if not empty
    if (!data.empty()) {
        buffer.write(data.data(), data.size());
    }
}

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
struct BufferData {
    uint32_t header;
    std::vector<uint8_t> data;
};

BufferData<> read_from_dynamic_buffer(hexi::dynamic_buffer<1024>& buffer, size_t data_length) {
    BufferData<> result;

    // Read header first (4 bytes for uint32_t)
    buffer.read(reinterpret_cast<uint8_t*>(&result.header), sizeof(result.header));

    // Read data of specified length
    if (data_length > 0) {
        result.data.resize(data_length);
        buffer.read(result.data.data(), data_length);
    }

    return result;
}
```

The implementation follows the patterns seen in the code fragments:

1. **Writing**: Uses `buffer.write()` to write the header (4 bytes for uint32_t) followed by the data array
2. **Reading**: Uses `buffer.read()` to read the header first, then reads the specified number of bytes for the data
3. **Error handling**: The code assumes the buffer has enough data (as seen in the test patterns)
4. **Type safety**: Proper casting between uint32_t and byte arrays using reinterpret_cast

The dynamic_buffer class appears to have standard read/write methods that take pointer and size parameters, similar to the patterns shown in the test files.

