Looking at the provided code fragments, I can see that `hexi::file_buffer` is a class for reading from files, and `hexi::binary_stream` is used for reading typed data. Here's the implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>

int32_t read_int32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    int32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}

float read_float_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    float value;
    stream >> value;

    return value;
}
```

However, based on the error handling examples, it would be better to add proper error checking. Here's a more robust version:

```cpp
#include <hexi/file_buffer.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <filesystem>
#include <stdexcept>

int32_t read_int32_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    int32_t value;
    stream >> value;

    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to read int32 from file");
    }

    return value;
}

float read_float_from_file(const std::filesystem::path& file_path) {
    hexi::file_buffer buffer(file_path);
    hexi::binary_stream stream(buffer);

    float value;
    stream >> value;

    if (!stream) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Failed to read float from file");
    }

    return value;
}
```

The key points from the code fragments:
- `hexi::file_buffer` is used to create a buffer from a file path
- `hexi::binary_stream` is created from the buffer and used to read typed data
- The stream extraction operator `>>` is used to read the values
- Error checking can be done by checking the stream state with `!stream` or `stream.state()`
- The `file_buffer` appears to be read-only based on the traits shown (`seeking: unsupported`)

