Looking at the provided code fragments, I can see how the Hexi library is used for serialization. The key insight is that the `serialise()` method of the object should be called with the stream writer/reader as a parameter.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

struct UserData {
    uint32_t user_id;
    std::string name;

    void serialise(auto& stream) {
        stream << user_id << name;
    }
};

void serialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const UserData& data) {
    // Create a non-const copy since serialise() might modify the object
    // but we have a const reference, so we need to work around this
    UserData non_const_data = data;
    non_const_data.serialise(writer);
}

void deserialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader, UserData& data) {
    data.serialise(reader);
}
```

The implementation works as follows:

1. **`serialize_object`**: Since we have a `const UserData&` but the `serialise()` method might modify the object (though in this case it shouldn't), we create a non-const copy and call `serialise()` on it with the writer.

2. **`deserialize_object`**: We simply call the `serialise()` method on the target object with the reader, which will populate the object's fields from the binary stream.

This follows the pattern shown in the code fragments where objects have a `serialise()` method that works with both reading and writing streams using the same `<<` operator syntax.

